</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="87" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
<taxonomicName authority="Robertson, 1902" authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Trachandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trachandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trachandrena</taxonomicName>
Robertson, 1902: 187, 189.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="87" type="type species">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena rugosa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Andrena rugosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Robertson, 1891, by original designation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="87" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
<taxonomicName authority="Robertson, 1902" authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Trachandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trachandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Trachandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, particularly the females, are relatively easy to recognize among most other subgenera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Andrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Nearctic region based on the combination of the coarsely rugose metapostnotum (i.e., propodeal triangle) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Dorsal enclosure of propodeum (i. e., propodeal triangle) of a female Andrena rugosa Robertson, the type species of Trachandrena Robertson." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.53704.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425256" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">1</figureCitation>
) and the generally coarse body sculpturing (being less strongly sculptured in most other subgenera), the structure of the metasomal terga, especially T2, which have broad apical marginal zones that usually extend 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Â½">1/2</normalizedToken>
the median length of the tergum (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Dorsal surface of metasoma of female Trachandrena. A Andrena rugosa, the type species of the subgenus, with relatively wide apical impressed area of T 2; B A. hippotes Robertson, with a relatively narrow apical impressed area of T 2 (but still wider than basal area); C A. cleodora (Viereck); D A. hadfieldi, nov. sp. Both of the latter species have broad apical impressed areas of T 2 which are impunctate." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.53704.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425257" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">2B</figureCitation>
) or more (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Dorsal surface of metasoma of female Trachandrena. A Andrena rugosa, the type species of the subgenus, with relatively wide apical impressed area of T 2; B A. hippotes Robertson, with a relatively narrow apical impressed area of T 2 (but still wider than basal area); C A. cleodora (Viereck); D A. hadfieldi, nov. sp. Both of the latter species have broad apical impressed areas of T 2 which are impunctate." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.53704.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425257" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">2A, C, D</figureCitation>
) (other subgenera in the Nearctic have narrower marginal zones), and the characteristic structure of the facial fovea, which is typically much narrower in the lower half (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Facial fovea of Andrena rugosa. The lower half of the facial fovea in Trachandrena is usually much narrower than the upper portion, though this species is the most extreme example." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.53704.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425258" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">3</figureCitation>
) (more parallel-sided for entire length in other Nearctic subgenera). As indicated above, in the Nearctic region 
<taxonomicName authority="Robertson, 1902" authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Trachandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trachandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Trachandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Hedicke, 1933" authorityName="Hedicke" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Plastandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plastandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Plastandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Viereck" authorityYear="1922" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Scrapteropsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" lsidName="Scrapteropsis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Scrapteropsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In addition to both of these subgenera having terga with much narrower marginal zones (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Dorsal surface of metasoma of female A Plastandrena Hedicke, Andrena crataegi Robertson, and B Scrapteropsis Viereck, A. kalmiae Atwood. Both subgenera differ from Trachandrena Robertson in having the apical impressed area of T 2 narrower than the basal area." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.53704.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425259" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">4</figureCitation>
), both sexes of 
<taxonomicName authority="Hedicke, 1933" authorityName="Hedicke" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Plastandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plastandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Plastandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
usually have weakly to strongly curved inner hind tibial spurs (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Inner hind tibial spur of A Plastandrena, Andrena crataegi, and B Trachandrena, A. hippotes." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.53704.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425260" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">5A</figureCitation>
) whereas these are straight in 
<taxonomicName authority="Robertson, 1902" authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Trachandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trachandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Trachandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Inner hind tibial spur of A Plastandrena, Andrena crataegi, and B Trachandrena, A. hippotes." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.53704.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425260" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">5B</figureCitation>
), and the facial fovea of females of both subgenera are typically broad throughout. Males of 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Viereck" authorityYear="1922" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Scrapteropsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" lsidName="Scrapteropsis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Scrapteropsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are difficult to distinguish from 
<taxonomicName authority="Robertson, 1902" authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Trachandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trachandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Trachandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.4039/Ent5619-1" author="Viereck, HL" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" pagination="19 - 24" refId="B17" refString="Viereck, HL, 1924. Prodromus of Andrena, a genus of bees. The Canadian Entomologist 56 (1): 19 - 24, DOI: https://doi.org/10.4039/Ent5619-1" title="Prodromus of Andrena, a genus of bees." url="https://doi.org/10.4039/Ent5619-1" volume="56" year="1924">Viereck 1924</bibRefCitation>
), though each has unique genital capsules (
<bibRefCitation author="LaBerge, WE" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" pagination="441 - 520" publicationUrl="https://www.jstor.org/stable/25078019" refId="B7" refString="LaBerge, WE, 1971. A revision of the bees of the genus Andrena of the Western Hemisphere. Part IV. Scrapteropsis, Xiphandrena and Rhaphandrena. Transactions of the American Entomological Society 97: 441 - 520, https://www.jstor.org/stable/25078019" title="A revision of the bees of the genus Andrena of the Western Hemisphere. Part IV. Scrapteropsis, Xiphandrena and Rhaphandrena." url="https://www.jstor.org/stable/25078019" volume="97" year="1971">LaBerge 1971</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="LaBerge, WE" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" pagination="235 - 371" publicationUrl="https://www.jstor.org/stable/25078133" refId="B8" refString="LaBerge, WE, 1973. A revision of the bees of the genus Andrena of the Western Hemisphere. Part VI. Subgenus Trachandrena. Transactions of the American Entomological Society 99: 235 - 371, https://www.jstor.org/stable/25078133" title="A revision of the bees of the genus Andrena of the Western Hemisphere. Part VI. Subgenus Trachandrena." url="https://www.jstor.org/stable/25078133" volume="99" year="1973">1973</bibRefCitation>
), the marginal zone of T2 is longer in 
<taxonomicName authority="Robertson, 1902" authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Trachandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trachandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Trachandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the antenna usually being slightly longer. Male 
<taxonomicName authority="Robertson, 1902" authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Trachandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trachandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Trachandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also have S6 usually flat, not with a reflexed apical margin or with apicolateral teeth as in some 
<taxonomicName authority="Hedicke, 1933" authorityName="Hedicke" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Plastandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plastandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Plastandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(i.e., 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. crataegi" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" rank="species" species="crataegi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">A. crataegi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="LaBerge, WE" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" pagination="1 - 47" publicationUrl="https://www.jstor.org/stable/25077972" refId="B6" refString="LaBerge, WE, 1969. A revision of the bees of the genus Andrena of the Western Hemisphere. Part II. Plastandrena, Aporandrena, Charitandrena. Transactions of the American Entomological Society 95: 1 - 47, https://www.jstor.org/stable/25077972" title="A revision of the bees of the genus Andrena of the Western Hemisphere. Part II. Plastandrena, Aporandrena, Charitandrena." url="https://www.jstor.org/stable/25077972" volume="95" year="1969">LaBerge 1969</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Michener, CD" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" refId="B12" refString="Michener, CD, 2007. The Bees of the World. Second Edition. The Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore. xv + 953 pp." title="The Bees of the World. Second Edition. The Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore. xv + 953 pp." year="2007">Michener 2007</bibRefCitation>
). In addition, most 
<taxonomicName authority="Hedicke, 1933" authorityName="Hedicke" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Plastandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plastandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Plastandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in North America, excluding 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. crataegi" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" rank="species" species="crataegi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">A. crataegi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, have the clypeus yellow or otherwise maculated (
<bibRefCitation author="LaBerge, WE" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" pagination="1 - 47" publicationUrl="https://www.jstor.org/stable/25077972" refId="B6" refString="LaBerge, WE, 1969. A revision of the bees of the genus Andrena of the Western Hemisphere. Part II. Plastandrena, Aporandrena, Charitandrena. Transactions of the American Entomological Society 95: 1 - 47, https://www.jstor.org/stable/25077972" title="A revision of the bees of the genus Andrena of the Western Hemisphere. Part II. Plastandrena, Aporandrena, Charitandrena." url="https://www.jstor.org/stable/25077972" volume="95" year="1969">LaBerge 1969</bibRefCitation>
), not black as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Robertson, 1902" authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Trachandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trachandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Trachandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/jhr.77.53704.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425256" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" start="Figure 1" startId="F1">
