<caption doi="10.3897/jhr.77.53704.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425258" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" start="Figure 3" startId="F3">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Figure 3.</emphasis>
Facial fovea of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena rugosa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Andrena rugosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The lower half of the facial fovea in 
<taxonomicName authority="Robertson, 1902" authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Trachandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trachandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Trachandrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is usually much narrower than the upper portion, though this species is the most extreme example.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption doi="10.3897/jhr.77.53704.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425259" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" start="Figure 4" startId="F4">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Figure 4.</emphasis>
Dorsal surface of metasoma of female 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">A</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Hedicke, 1933" authorityName="Hedicke" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Plastandrena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plastandrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Plastandrena</emphasis>
